Alimentary canal.
The esophagus, without glands and cilia (
Fig. 2C
), opens into the ventral side of posterior rhynchodaeum. The stomach, which is about 
1.3–2.8 mm
in length, is divided into two regions. The short anterior region is about 10% of the full stomach length, and is characterized by a larger number of red- staining and smaller number of blue-staining glands (
Fig. 2F
). At the long posterior stomach region, the wall becomes thinner, the number of gland cells decreases markedly. The intestine possesses distinct unbranched diverticula (
Fig. 1G
) but no caecum.

Nervous system.
The brain is composed of paired ventral and dorsal ganglia. The dorsal and the ventral cerebral commissures are about 10 and 25 µm thick, respectively (
Fig. 2C
). The lateral nerve cord is about 25 µm in diameter (
Fig. 2D
); there is no accessory lateral nerve.

Frontal organ and cephalic glands.
The frontal organ, opening in front of proboscis pore, is a simple epithelial pit about 6 µm in diameter (
Fig. 2A
). Cephalic glands (
Fig. 2B
), which are scarcely stained by Mallory, extend back to the foregut region. Parenchyma is scarcely developed.
